IMHO, this feature could give us some super powers by using lodash, without the need of creating new functions/modules or APIs. For example when using _.filter, we would have right away: 

* **A way to define an OR clause** (e.g. property matches with *'this'* or *'that'*)
* **Partial matching** (e.g. look for *'th'* to match *'this'* or *'that'*)
* **Case-Insensitive** (e.g. *'JavaScript'* will match with *'javascript'*)

I will give some use cases examples through code:

```javascript
const modules = [{
	name: 'filterBy1',
	language: 'JavaScript',
	version: '1.0.0'
},{
	name: 'sortBy1',
	language: 'JavaScript',
	version: '2.1.0'
}, {
	name: 'filterBy2',
	language: 'Python',
	version: '1.2.1'
}, {
	name: 'sortBy2',
	language: 'Go',
	version: '3.2.1'
}];

// Only languages JavaScript or Python (OR CLAUSE + CASE-INSENSITIVE)
_.filter(modules, { language: /javascript|Python/i });

// Only versions 1.* (PARTIAL MATCHING)
_.filter(modules, { version: /^1.*/ });

// Only modules which has "filter" in the name, for JavaScript language (CASE-INSENSITIVE + PARTIAL MATCHING)
_.filter(modules, {
	name: /filter/i,
	language: /javascript/i
});

// SOME EXAMPLES USING _.isMatch instead of _.filter

// Is the first module language equal to JavaScript or Python
_.isMatch(modules[0], { language: /JavaScript|Python/i }); // true

// Is the first module language equal to Python or Go
_.isMatch(modules[0], { language: /Python|Go/i }); // false
```

